                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d960">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">611.003 Rayon/5</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by the Under Secretary of State</hi> (<hi
                        rend="italic">Phillips</hi>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-07-19">July 19,
                            1935</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>The Japanese Ambassador called this morning to present his new Counselor of
                    Embassy, Mr. Seijiro Yoshizawa, who has just arrived in Washington and who will
                    act for the Ambassador in the latter’s absence in Connecticut during the summer
                    months.</p>
                <p>Before leaving the Ambassador expressed his thanks and appreciation for the help
                    which the Department gave in removing the danger <pb facs="1097" n="985"
                        xml:id="pg_985"/> of a tax on rayon [and] silk. He said that he had received
                    no instructions to express these views, but that this morning he was in receipt
                    of various telegrams of gratification from private parties, and was very glad
                    for the occasion to express his own sentiments.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">William Phillips</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
